-- 22: Patan Museum
(22, 'The Museum Behind the Golden Door', 'Architecture', 4,
'The Patan Museum, housed within the restored royal palace of the Malla kings on the eastern side of Patan Durbar Square, is widely considered the finest museum in South Asia for the presentation of Himalayan art and sacred objects. Entering through the famous gilded Golden Door (Sun Dhoka) — whose toranas and repoussé panels are a masterpiece of Newar metalwork — visitors step from the busy Durbar Square into a world of extraordinary beauty and scholarship. The museum''s permanent collection presents over 1,500 pieces of Hindu and Buddhist art in their cultural context, with interpretive panels that explain not just what each object is but how it was used in ritual life. Unlike many museums where objects feel removed from meaning, the Patan Museum keeps the sacred dimension of each piece alive. The restored courtyards, with their carved wooden windows and stone fountains, are themselves part of the exhibit — the museum building IS the heritage.',
'The palace was built in the 17th century during the reign of the Malla kings of Patan. It was later restored through a joint Nepal-Austrian heritage project that took two decades, reopening as a museum in 1997. The restoration involved cataloguing and conserving thousands of individual architectural elements while keeping the building''s historical integrity.',
'The Patan Museum is a model for how heritage buildings can be adaptively reused to tell their own story. It demonstrates that the context of an object — the palace whose craftsmen made it, the courtyard where it was used — is as important as the object itself.',
ARRAY['https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/55/Patan_Museum.jpg','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/04/Patan_Museum%2C_The_Museum_behind_the_Golden_Door_1.jpg','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d2/Patan_Museum%2C_The_Museum_behind_the_Golden_Door.jpg'],
NOW(), NOW()),

-- 23: National Museum of Nepal
(23, 'The Nation''s Memory in One Building', 'History', 4,
'The National Museum of Nepal in Chhauni, Kathmandu, holds the largest and most comprehensive collection of Nepali art, artefacts, and historical objects in the country. Spread across several buildings within a garden compound, the museum covers Nepal''s history from prehistoric times through the unification period and into the modern era. Highlights include an extraordinary collection of stone sculptures from the Licchavi period (4th–9th century CE), bronze statues that rank among the finest examples of Himalayan Buddhist metalwork, and a natural history gallery with specimens documenting Nepal''s remarkable biodiversity. The arms and armour gallery tells the story of the Gorkha military tradition through weapons, uniforms, and trophies from Nepal''s wars. For anyone seeking to understand the full sweep of Nepali history and culture in a single visit, the National Museum is the essential starting point.',
'The museum was established in 1928 in a building originally constructed as an armoury during the Rana period. The collection has grown through acquisition, donation, and salvage of objects from across the country. Many pieces in the collection were recovered from the illegal antiquities trade or donated by families following the 2015 earthquake.',
'The National Museum preserves objects that represent the entire cultural heritage of Nepal — from all regions, ethnic groups, and religious traditions. It is the principal institution for the study of Nepali art history and serves as a reference point for authentication of antique objects.',
ARRAY['https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/22/Building_of_National_Museum_of_Nepal_%281%29.jpg','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/0d/Building_of_National_Museum_of_Nepal_%282%29.jpg','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/da/Artifacts_at_National_Museum_of_Nepal_%281%29.jpg'],
NOW(), NOW()),

-- 29: Kathesimbhu Stupa
(29, 'The Valley''s Swayambhu — For Those Who Cannot Climb', 'Legend', 3,
'Kathesimbhu Stupa in the old bazaar neighbourhood of Thamel is a small but deeply revered Buddhist stupa with an intriguing legend: it was built for the elderly and infirm who could not manage the steep climb to Swayambhunath, with the same spiritual merit believed to accrue from circumambulating it as from the great hill-top stupa itself. The stupa''s whitewashed dome, painted with the all-seeing eyes of the Buddha, occupies a busy courtyard surrounded by small temples, prayer wheels, and the day-to-day life of the Thamel neighbourhood. Pigeons gather by the hundreds on the stupa''s terraces, and the constant turning of prayer wheels by passing worshippers gives the courtyard a perpetual sense of gentle devotion. Despite Thamel''s transformation into Kathmandu''s main tourist district, Kathesimbhu remains a living neighbourhood shrine, a quiet centre of Buddhist practice in the midst of the city''s bustle.',
'The stupa is believed to date to the 17th century CE and was built to replicate the power of Swayambhunath for those unable to make the pilgrimage to the hill. The surrounding area was historically a Newar Buddhist neighbourhood before the growth of the tourist trade transformed Thamel.',
'Kathesimbhu illustrates how Buddhist practice in Nepal adapts to human needs — creating multiple access points to merit and devotion for people of different physical abilities. The stupa remains an active worship site and the centre of the surviving Buddhist community in the Thamel area.',
ARRAY['https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/39/Buddha%27s_eyes_on_the_Kathesimbhu_stupa_%2817210992643%29.jpg','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/db/Buddhist_complex_in_the_old_city_%2812653801864%29.jpg','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/20/A_stoupa_surrounded_by_pigeons.JPG'],
NOW(), NOW()),

-- 30: Charumati Stupa
(30, 'Ashoka''s Daughter and the Stupa She Left Behind', 'History', 3,
'Charumati Stupa in the Chabahil neighbourhood of Kathmandu is one of four stupas in the valley traditionally attributed to Emperor Ashoka''s daughter, Charumati, who legend says married a Nepali nobleman and settled in the valley. Of the four Ashokan-era stupas — at Chabahil, Patan (four cardinal stupas), and Swayambhunath complex — Charumati is the one directly named for her. The small whitewashed stupa sits in a quiet courtyard away from the main tourist trail, making it one of the more peaceful places in the city to contemplate Nepal''s ancient connections to the Buddhist world. The surrounding neighbourhood of Chabahil has its own older Chabahil Stupa nearby, also linked to the Ashokan tradition, creating a cluster of ancient Buddhist monuments in what is otherwise a modern residential area.',
'Archaeological evidence suggests Buddhist activity in the Chabahil area dating to the 3rd century BCE, consistent with the Ashokan attribution. The stupa has been rebuilt and renovated multiple times over the centuries. The tradition connecting it to Charumati is recorded in the Vamsavali (royal chronicles) of the valley.',
'Charumati Stupa represents the oldest layer of Buddhism in the Kathmandu Valley, predating even the Licchavi kingdom. Its quiet, non-commercial atmosphere makes it a valuable counterpoint to the busier heritage sites and a place where the continuity of Buddhist practice across 2,300 years can be felt.',
ARRAY['https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/49/Charumati_Stupa.jpg','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/27/Charumati_Stupa.JPG','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/86/Charumati_Stupa_Image_01.jpg'],
NOW(), NOW()),

-- 35: Swargadwari Temple
(35, 'The Gate of Heaven in the Western Hills', 'Legend', 4,
'Swargadwari — the Gate of Heaven — is a sacred Hindu ashram and temple complex perched on a mountain ridge at 1,920 metres in Pyuthan district in western Nepal, one of the most spiritually significant sites in the mid-western hills. The site is associated with the legendary sage Vedavyasa, the author of the Mahabharata, who is said to have meditated here. The name refers to the belief that dying at or near this sacred place grants direct passage to heaven (swarga). The complex includes the main temple to Swargadwari Dham, a series of smaller shrines, and an ashram where resident sadhus perform continuous Vedic fire rituals (yajna). The annual Swargadwari Mela pilgrimage festival, held in the month of Baisakh (April–May), draws hundreds of thousands of devotees from across the mid-western hills — one of the largest religious gatherings in Nepal outside the Kathmandu Valley.',
'The site''s religious significance is deeply rooted in the Vaishnava and Shaiva traditions of western Nepal. The ashram was formally organised in the 20th century by a lineage of Hindu teachers who established the current temple complex and festival traditions. Road access was built only recently, making the pilgrimage less arduous than historically.',
'For the communities of Pyuthan, Rolpa, Arghakhanchi, and surrounding districts, Swargadwari is the most important religious destination in the region — the equivalent of Pashupatinath for Kathmandu. The festival brings together people from dozens of ethnic and caste backgrounds in shared devotion.',
ARRAY['https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d9/View_of_mountain_range_from_swargadwari.JPG','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/01/Gosaikunda_Lake.jpg','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/96/Mountain_on_which_Pathibhara_Temple_is_located.jpg'],
NOW(), NOW()),

-- 38: Bhimsen Temple Patan
(38, 'The God of Merchants and Strength', 'Cultural', 3,
'Bhimsen Temple in Patan Durbar Square is dedicated to Bhimsen — the second of the five Pandava brothers in the Mahabharata, celebrated for his legendary physical strength. In Nepal, Bhimsen is uniquely worshipped as the patron deity of merchants and traders, a role not found in Indian Hindu tradition. This local evolution of the deity reflects the Newar merchant community''s need for a powerful divine protector in their commercial endeavours along the Himalayan trade routes to Tibet and India. The temple''s ground floor was historically used as a trading hall, blending the commercial and sacred in a way typical of Newar religious culture. The five-storey pagoda temple stands prominently on the south side of Patan Durbar Square, its whitewashed lower storey contrasting with the brick and tile upper floors. On the first day of every month and on auspicious Bhimsen festivals, merchants from across the valley bring offerings to ensure success in business.',
'The temple was built in the 17th century CE and has been renovated multiple times. Bhimsen worship among Newar merchants is believed to date to the Malla period when Patan was a major trading city. The lower hall of the temple served as a commercial space, reflecting the integration of trade and religious life in Newar society.',
'Bhimsen''s role as merchant deity shows how Newar Buddhism and Hinduism adapted pan-South Asian religious figures to meet the specific needs of their community. The temple is an active centre of commercial prayer — a reminder that for Nepal''s trading communities, spiritual and economic life have never been separate.',
ARRAY['https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/55/Panoroma_of_Patan_durbar_Square.jpg','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a0/Patan_Durbar_Squar-IMG_3217.jpg','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/ff/Patan_Durbar_Square_01.jpg'],
NOW(), NOW()),

-- 39: Tribhuvan Museum
(39, 'The King Who Chose India Over the Palace', 'History', 4,
'The Tribhuvan Museum, housed within the Hanuman Dhoka Palace complex in Kathmandu Durbar Square, commemorates King Tribhuvan Bir Bikram Shah — the monarch who ended the century-long Rana oligarchy and restored democratic rights to Nepal in 1951. The museum preserves the royal apartments used by Tribhuvan and his family, including the room where he secretly sheltered the leaders of the anti-Rana movement, and the personal objects that tell the story of a king who risked his throne to free his people. In 1950, Tribhuvan famously sought asylum in the Indian Embassy in Kathmandu and flew to India, breaking the Rana prime ministers'' grip on power and triggering the political revolution that ended their rule. The palace rooms feel intimate rather than grand — a family home rather than a state monument — and the personal dimension of the story gives the museum an emotional quality that purely historical exhibits rarely achieve.',
'King Tribhuvan reigned from 1911 to 1955 but was effectively powerless under the Rana system until 1951. His flight to the Indian Embassy in November 1950, joined by most of the royal family, was the decisive act that broke the Ranas'' power. He is revered as the "Father of the Nation" in Nepal and his image appeared on Nepali currency for decades.',
'The Tribhuvan Museum makes the abstract story of Nepal''s democratisation concrete and personal. Seeing the king''s actual living space and possessions, and understanding the physical risk he took by seeking asylum, gives visitors a vivid sense of one of the most significant moments in modern Nepali history.',
ARRAY['https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/69/Historic_Pagoda_Style_Architecture_in_Kathmandu_Durbar_Square-IMG_4069.jpg','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/48/Basantapurdurbarsquare.jpg','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/06/Hanuman_Dhoka_Durbar_Square.jpg'],
NOW(), NOW()),

-- 40: Pashupatinath Ghats
(40, 'Where Life Meets Death on the Sacred River', 'Cultural', 5,
'The cremation ghats of Pashupatinath on the banks of the Bagmati River are among the most profound and challenging places a visitor to Nepal can encounter. Here, on stone platforms descending to the sacred river, Nepali Hindus are cremated in open-air ceremonies attended by family members, in a process that is public, communal, and deeply human. Watching a cremation at the Arya Ghat is not voyeurism — it is witnessing one of the most honest engagements with death that any culture has developed. The smoke rises from multiple pyres simultaneously, sadhus sit in meditation on the opposite bank, and pilgrims bathe in the river upstream in acts of purification. The river itself — polluted but sacred — receives the ashes. Death here is not hidden away but integrated into the fabric of daily life, seen and accepted. The ghats extend for several hundred metres along the river, each section associated with particular rituals, castes, or royal ceremonies.',
'The Pashupatinath ghats have been a cremation site for at least 1,500 years, possibly much longer. The Arya Ghat on the southern bank is reserved for members of the royal family and high-caste Hindus. The northern ghats serve the broader Hindu community. The Bagmati is considered a sacred river equivalent to the Ganges, and cremation on its banks is believed to guarantee the soul''s liberation.',
'The ghats embody a relationship with death that is increasingly rare in the modern world — open, communal, and spiritually integrated. For Hindus, cremation on the Bagmati in the shadow of Pashupatinath is the most auspicious end to a human life. For visitors, the experience is often described as one of the most memorable and perspective-shifting of any journey in Nepal.',
ARRAY['https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/32/Bagmati_River_and_Pashupatinath.jpg','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d3/Pashupati_Kshetra_1.jpg','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/3e/Pashupatinath_temple.JPG'],
NOW(), NOW()),

-- 41: Doleshwar Mahadev
(41, 'The Southern Head of Kedarnath', 'Legend', 4,
'Doleshwar Mahadev Temple in Suryabinayak, Bhaktapur district, holds a remarkable claim in the Hindu pilgrimage geography of South Asia: it is believed to be the mukha (face/head) of the Kedarnath Shiva lingam in the Himalayas of Uttarakhand, India. According to tradition, when the Pandava brothers sought Shiva after the Kurukshetra war to atone for the killing of their kinsmen, Shiva fled from them in the form of a bull. When they finally caught him, different parts of the bull''s body sank into the earth at different locations — and these locations became the Panch Kedar (five Kedar) pilgrimage sites. The face of the bull is said to have appeared at Doleshwar in Nepal, making it a site of equal sanctity to Kedarnath itself. This belief was formally recognised by the Kedarnath Temple Trust in 2009, cementing Doleshwar''s place in the all-India pilgrimage circuit and bringing thousands of Indian pilgrims to this previously quiet Bhaktapur hillside temple.',
'The temple has existed in Suryabinayak for centuries but gained international prominence only in 2009 when the Archaeological Survey of India and the Kedarnath temple authorities formally recognised its connection to the Panch Kedar mythology. The recognition was based on textual evidence in ancient Puranic texts and local oral traditions.',
'Doleshwar Mahadev shows how pilgrimage geography in Hinduism connects distant sites into a unified sacred landscape. A temple in the Bhaktapur hills is cosmologically linked to one of the holiest Himalayan shrines, making Nepal an integral part of the pan-South Asian Hindu pilgrimage world.',
ARRAY['https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/89/Doleshwar_Mahadev.jpg','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/15/Doleshor_Mahadev.jpg','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/3b/Doleshwor_mahadev_%28Nepal%29_23_53_05_793000.jpeg'],
NOW(), NOW()),

-- 44: Shechen Monastery
(44, 'A Tibetan Monastery Reborn in Nepal', 'History', 3,
'Shechen Tennyi Dargyeling Monastery near Boudhanath in Kathmandu is one of the most important Nyingma school Tibetan Buddhist monasteries in the world, rebuilt in Nepal after its original in Tibet was destroyed during the Cultural Revolution. The monastery was re-established in 1980 by Dilgo Khyentse Rinpoche — one of the most revered Tibetan Buddhist masters of the 20th century — who chose the area near Boudhanath for its sacred significance and its established Tibetan exile community. The monastery''s main temple is decorated with exquisite traditional thangka paintings and houses a large statue of Padmasambhava (Guru Rinpoche), the 8th-century master who brought Buddhism from India to Tibet. A three-year retreat centre operates within the complex, and the monastery runs schools for young monks. The current head of the monastery, Rabjam Rinpoche, continues the lineage of teachings transmitted from the original Shechen monastery in Kham, eastern Tibet.',
'Shechen monastery in Tibet was one of the six "mother monasteries" of the Nyingma school and one of the greatest centres of Buddhist scholarship in eastern Tibet before its destruction in the 1960s. The Kathmandu rebuild preserves the lineage, the ritual tradition, the texts, and the artistic style of the original institution.',
'Shechen represents the broader story of Tibetan Buddhism''s survival and continuation outside Tibet — a tradition that might have been entirely severed has instead found new roots in Nepal, India, and ultimately worldwide. The monastery is a living institution, not a museum piece.',
ARRAY['https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/cf/Shechen_Monastery%2C_Nepal.jpg','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/b1/Shechen_Monastery_4-May-2016.jpg','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c1/Boudhanath_Stupa_1.JPG'],
NOW(), NOW()),

-- 45: Phewa Lake Barahi Temple
(45, 'The Goddess on the Lake', 'Legend', 3,
'The Barahi Temple on Phewa Lake is Pokhara''s most iconic religious image — a small pagoda temple perched on a tiny forested island in the middle of the lake, with the snow-capped Annapurna massif rising beyond it on clear mornings. Dedicated to Barahi, a tantric form of the goddess Durga, the temple is reached only by wooden rowboat from the lakeside ghats. The journey across the water, with the mountains reflected in the lake surface and the sound of oars dipping, is itself a meditative transition between the commercial world of the lakeside and the sacred space of the island. Devotees come to offer animals, flowers, and incense to the goddess, who is believed to protect Pokhara from natural disasters. On Saturdays, the ghats are busy with families waiting for boats, and the temple island hums with activity. The combination of the island setting, the lake reflection, and the Himalayan backdrop makes this one of the most visually spectacular small temples in all of Nepal.',
'The Barahi Temple was established by the ruling family of the Kaski kingdom as a protective deity for the region. Pokhara was the most important city of the Kaski principality before Nepal''s unification in 1768. The goddess Barahi remains the principal protective deity of the Pokhara valley.',
'The Barahi Temple is inseparable from the identity of Pokhara — its image on the lake with the mountains behind has become the defining visual symbol of the city. The boat journey to the temple is a ritual in itself, and the island''s forested peace amid the busy lakeside is one of Pokhara''s most valued experiences.',
ARRAY['https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d4/Barahi_Island_Temple%2C_Phewa_Lake%2C_Pokhara%2C_Nepal.JPG','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a0/Barahi_mandir_Pokhara.jpg','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e5/Phewa_Lake_and_Taal_Barahi_Temple.jpg'],
NOW(), NOW()),

-- 46: Bikram Sambat Museum
(46, 'The Calendar That Sets Nepal Apart', 'Cultural', 3,
'The Bikram Sambat Museum in Bhaktapur celebrates Nepal''s official calendar system — the Bikram Sambat (BS) — which runs 56 years and 8.5 months ahead of the Gregorian calendar. Nepal is one of the very few countries in the world to use a non-Gregorian calendar as its official civil calendar: all government documents, festivals, and daily life in Nepal follow the BS calendar. The museum explains the history and astronomy of the Bikram Sambat system, which is a lunisolar calendar based on the ancient Hindu calendar tradition and named for the legendary King Vikramaditya of Ujjain, India. The exhibit shows how the calendar governs the timing of all major festivals, agricultural seasons, and religious observances in Nepal. Understanding Nepal''s calendar system opens a window into the distinctly Nepali way of marking time — a rhythm of festivals and seasons that differs from the Gregorian world and gives Nepali cultural life much of its distinctive character.',
'The Bikram Sambat era began in 57 BCE, according to tradition, with the reign of King Vikramaditya. Nepal adopted it as the official civil calendar, and as of 2024 AD, Nepal is in BS 2081. The calendar''s 12 months have names derived from Sanskrit, and the new year (Baisakh 1) falls in mid-April.',
'The Bikram Sambat calendar is not merely a timekeeping system but a cultural framework that determines the entire rhythm of Nepali life — when farmers plant and harvest, when families gather for festivals, when offices close for national holidays. Understanding it is essential to understanding Nepal.',
ARRAY['https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/42/A_brief_view_of_Bhaktapur_Durbar_Square.JPG','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/88/Bhaktapur_Durban_Square.JPG','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/9f/Bhaktapur_Durbar_Square_041224_155.jpg'],
NOW(), NOW()),

-- 47: Lumbini Museum
(47, 'Artefacts From the Beginning of a World Religion', 'History', 3,
'The Lumbini Museum, located within the Lumbini development zone near the Maya Devi Temple, houses an important collection of artefacts excavated from the Lumbini area and related finds from across the Terai, documenting the ancient Buddhist civilisation that flourished in this region. The collection includes terracotta figurines, coins, ceramics, and architectural fragments dating from the Mauryan period (3rd century BCE) through the medieval era, as well as photographs, manuscripts, and replicas relating to the archaeological and pilgrimage history of Lumbini. For visitors coming to Lumbini as a spiritual destination, the museum provides essential historical and archaeological context — explaining the layers of civilisation discovered beneath and around the Maya Devi Temple and the evidence that places the Buddha''s birth here beyond reasonable doubt. The museum building itself is a modern structure designed to blend with the sacred garden landscape.',
'The museum was established to display and protect finds from the ongoing archaeological excavations at Lumbini, which have been conducted by the Lumbini Development Trust in collaboration with Japanese and international archaeological teams since the 1990s. Key discoveries include the Marker Stone beneath the Maya Devi Temple, which confirms the precise birthplace.',
'The Lumbini Museum bridges the gap between faith and history — it presents the archaeological evidence for Lumbini''s claims while also honouring the site''s status as one of the most sacred places on earth for hundreds of millions of people.',
ARRAY['https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/97/Lumbini_Museum.jpg','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c3/Maya_Devi_temple-Nepal.JPG','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/96/Maya_Devi_Temple_with_Monks.jpg'],
NOW(), NOW()),

-- 48: Swayambhu Natural History Museum
(48, 'Nepal''s Biodiversity in One Place', 'Cultural', 3,
'The Natural History Museum at Swayambhu in Kathmandu gives visitors a comprehensive introduction to Nepal''s extraordinary natural heritage — the country''s remarkable biodiversity that makes it one of the most ecologically significant nations on earth despite its small size. Nepal contains five climatic zones stacked vertically from tropical Terai plains to Arctic Himalayan summits, supporting an astonishing range of plant and animal life. The museum''s collections include specimens of Nepal''s 900 bird species (the eighth highest in the world), its mammals from tigers and elephants in the lowlands to snow leopards and Himalayan tahr in the mountains, its butterflies, reptiles, and fish. Geology exhibits explain how the Himalayas formed — the collision of the Indian and Eurasian tectonic plates pushing up the world''s highest mountain range over 50 million years. The museum is operated by Tribhuvan University and is used by students and researchers as well as general visitors.',
'The Natural History Museum was established in 1975 as part of Tribhuvan University''s Institute of Science and Technology. The Swayambhu hill location gives it a fitting setting — the hill''s own ecosystem supports several species not found elsewhere in the urban valley.',
'Nepal''s biodiversity is one of its most important but least-known assets. The country contains 8 of the world''s 14 highest mountains, 75% of the world''s climatic zones, and an extraordinary concentration of endemic species. The Natural History Museum makes this natural wealth visible and accessible.',
ARRAY['https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/31/Swayambhunath_Stupa_as_seen_from_Dharahara.JPG','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/1c/View_Of_Swayambhunath_stupa.jpg','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/9d/Eyes_of_swayambunath_stupa.jpg'],
NOW(), NOW()),

-- 50: Manakamana Cable Car
(50, 'The Mountain Wish-Fulfiller by Wire', 'Cultural', 3,
'The Manakamana Cable Car is Nepal''s first aerial ropeway and one of the most dramatic ways to reach any temple in the country — a 10-minute gondola ride over plunging gorges and forested ridges to reach the Manakamana Temple at 1,302 metres above the Marsyangdi valley. Before the cable car opened in 1998, reaching the goddess required a three-hour climb on foot — a journey that, while arduous, was itself considered part of the pilgrimage. The cable car was built with Austrian technology and carries pilgrims and tourists in glass-and-steel gondolas that swing gently over the valley, offering views of the Himalayan foothills and, on clear days, the snow-capped Annapurna and Manaslu ranges. The station at the bottom, near the town of Abu Khaireni on the Kathmandu-Pokhara highway, is the practical starting point. At the top, the cable car deposits visitors just steps from the temple complex. The juxtaposition of ancient pilgrimage tradition and modern engineering is pure Nepal — a country that moves between centuries in the space of a gondola ride.',
'The cable car was constructed by the Himalayan Cableway company and Doppelmayr Austria, opening in 1998. It was the first such installation in Nepal and has carried millions of passengers in the years since. The engineering challenge of spanning the deep valley gorge required careful planning given Nepal''s seismic activity.',
'The Manakamana Cable Car transformed the pilgrimage economics of the region, making the goddess accessible to elderly pilgrims, young children, and those with limited mobility who would never have managed the climb on foot. The cable car station area has developed into a significant tourist and commercial hub.',
ARRAY['https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c7/Manakamana_Cablecar_IMG_1593.jpg','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e6/Gorkha_Manakamana_Temple.jpg','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/aa/Manakamana_Temple_Mankamana_Gorkha_Nepal_Rajesh_Dhungana_%282%29.jpg'],
NOW(), NOW());


